<TITLE> Stocks close up, investors remain cautious </TITLE>
<TEXT>
 Dhaka, Feb 11 (bdnews24.com)Dhaka stocks finished higher Monday after losing the previous day amid retail investors' cautious stance. Turnover and trading volume however witnessed a fall from the previous day. Investors continued selling off to gain profits though at a lesser pace than Sunday, market observers said. DSE chief executive Salahuddin Ahmed Khan said that investors are being cautious about taking loans to buy shares. "Investors are reluctant to take loans from merchant banks and are also thinking twice before putting money in shares," he said. Yaweer sayeed, who manages over Tk1 billion in funds at AIMS of Bangladesh, agreed that investors are considering carefully before buying. "At the end of the day I would say that the market is in a positive trend and investors have started to behave maturely," he added. Dhaka Stock Exchange's general index kicked off with a fall in the opening hour of trade. It recovered losses in the second hour and remained more or less stable throughout the day to finish up. The benchmark DGEN or general index closed at 2977.66, up 2.27 points or 0.07 percent. The DSI or all share price index ended on 2503.07, up 0.72 points or 0.02 percent. The blue chip DSE-20 closed on 2357.36, rising 3.65 points, or 0.15 percent,. Turnover on the country's prime bourse fell to Tk 1.99 billion from Sunday's Tk 2.99 billion from 15,158,044 traded shares. Losers beat gainers 126 to 97, with eleven scrips holding steady. The day's trading was paced by shares in banks, mutual funds, lease financing companies and state run oil entities. Insurers fell significantly Monday after the gaining the previous day. AB Bank continued to top the turnover board from the previous day. It rose on rumours of issue of rights shares, closing at Tk 2913, up 1.47 percent. Summit Power continued to decline, ending 1.09 percent down at Tk 1583. Grameen Mutual Fund One also lost 0.16 percent to Tk 120.90. State owned Meghna Petroleum slipped 1.89 percent to end on Tk 341.80. IFIC Bank however, crept up 0.48 percent to Tk 2805. Among the other scrips on the turnover boardJamuna Oil, AIMS 1st Mutual Fund and BRAC Bank declined. IDLC and NBL advanced. Anwar Galvanising, Maq Enterprises, IDLC, BCIL and National Polymar emerged as major gainers. Among the day's top losers were Karnaphuli Insurance, Agrani Insurance, Mercantile Insurance, Asia Pacific General Insurance and Global Insurance. On the Chittagong Stock Exchange, eleven of the sixteen sectors fell with leasing & finance, textiles & clothing and banks advancing the most. Turnover slumped to Tk 320.83 million from 2, 562, 107 traded shares. The CSCX or selective categories index crept up 0.79 points, or 0.01 percent, to end on 4858.66. The CASPI or all share price index ended 1.97 points, or 0.02 percent, down at 7549.74.. The blue chip CSE-30 index rose 17.44 points, or 0.25 percent, to end on 6751.43. Of the traded issues 49 advanced, 80 declined and five remained unchanged. bd
